Is a relation a function? And is the function one-to-one?

Relation

  • A relation associates some elements of one set (called the domain) with some elements of another set (called the range). There are many ways to express relations:
  • Segments connecting elements of sets:


  • A list of ordered pairs

\[( 3 , 1 )~~( 5 , 9 )~~( 6 , 7 )~~( 8 , 5 )~~( 9 , 7 )\]

  • A plot of points


  • In this case, the domain is {3, 5, 6, 8, 9}
  • In this case, the range is {1, 5, 7, 9}

Is relation a function?

  • We say \(y\) is a function of \(x\) if the relation passes the vertical line test.
  • Lets see an example that FAILS the vertical line test, thus meaning that \(y\) is not a function of \(x\).


  • Notice as ordered pairs, we see the same \(x\) value (5) paired with two different \(y\) values (3 and 7), and that indicated that \(y\) is not a function of \(x\). \[( 3 , 1 )~~( 5 , 3 )~~( 5 , 7 )~~( 8 , 4 )~~( 9 , 2 )\]
  • And we see \(y\) is not a function of \(x\) in set connections as a v shape in the left column.


Is reverse relation a function?

  • We say \(x\) is a function of \(y\) if the relation passes the horizontal line test.
  • Lets see an example that FAILS the horizontal line test, thus meaning that \(x\) is not a function of \(y\).


  • Notice as ordered pairs, we see the same \(y\) value (7) paired with two different \(x\) values (6 and 8), and that indicated that \(x\) is not a function of \(y\). \[( 3 , 1 )~~( 5 , 3 )~~( 6 , 7 )~~( 8 , 7 )~~( 9 , 2 )\]
  • And we see \(x\) is not a function of \(y\) in set connections as a v shape in the right column.


Is the relation a one-to-one function?

  • If:
    • \(y\) is a function of \(x\)
    • AND
    • \(x\) is a function of \(y\)
  • Then the function is one-to-one.

Here is an example of a one-to-one function:


\[( 3 , 1 )~~( 5 , 3 )~~( 6 , 7 )~~( 8 , 5 )~~( 9 , 2 )\]


A relation can be neither a function mapping \(x\) to \(y\) nor a function mapping \(y\) to \(x\).

  • If:
    • \(y\) is NOT a function of \(x\)
    • AND
    • \(x\) is NOT a function of \(y\)
  • Then the relation is not a function in either direction.

Here is an example:


\[( 3 , 1 )~~( 5 , 3 )~~( 6 , 3 )~~( 8 , 5 )~~( 8 , 2 )\]


We do


  • Is \(y\) a function of \(x\)? (Does it pass vertical line test?)
  • Is \(x\) a function of \(y\)? (Does it pass horizontal line test?)
  • Is there a one-to-one function? (Does it pass both tests?)

A relation is expressed as a list of ordered \((x,y)\) pairs.

\[( 1 , 1 )~~( 3 , 4 )~~( 5 , 8 )~~( 5 , 8 )~~( 7 , 5 )~~( 8 , 4 )\]

  • Is \(y\) a function of \(x\)? (Does it pass vertical line test?)
  • Is \(x\) a function of \(y\)? (Does it pass horizontal line test?)
  • Is there a one-to-one function? (Does it pass both tests?)

  • Is \(y\) a function of \(x\)?
  • Is \(x\) a function of \(y\)?
  • Is there a one-to-one function?

  • Is \(y\) a function of \(x\)?
  • Is \(x\) a function of \(y\)?
  • Is there a one-to-one function?
